undescended testes

What are some histologic changes in cryptorchidism?

Histologic changes in the malpositioned testis begin as early as 2 years of age. 

They are characterized by an arrest in the development of germ cells associated with marked hyalinization and thickening of the basement membrane of the spermatic tubules

the protrusion or passage of a peritoneal sac, with or without abdominal contents,
through a weakened part of the abdominal wall in the groin. Can be direct or indirect
What is an indirect inguinal hernia?

• Enabled by patent processus vaginalis.
  • Protrusion of peritoneal sac entering the inguinal canal by passing through the deep inguinal ring. 
  • Extent of excursion depends on amount of processus vaginalis that remains patent
  • Protrusion may extend into scrotum for men and labia majus for women
What is a direct inguinal hernia?

• Peritoneal sac bulges through weakened abdominal wall.
  • Through Hesselbach's triangle
  • May exit through superficial inguinal ring (but does not go through deep inguinal ring)

bounded:
laterally by the inferior epigastric artery;
medially by the rectus abdominis muscle;
inferiorly by the inguinal ligament
Urological emergency. Twisting of spermatic cord resulting in venous engorgement that causes arterial compromise and irreversible damage if torsion is not resolved in 6-12hrs
What clinical findings will you find in testicular torsion?

• sudden-onset unilateral testicular pain (may radiate to the lower abdomen)
  • swollen and tender testicle
  • nausea and vomiting
  • high-riding testicle with transverse lie
  • -ve cremasteric reflex
  • Prehn's sign -ve
What are the 2 main age presentations of testicular torsion?

Neonatal (entire tunica vaginalis undergoes torsion (extravaginal torsion), no associated anatomical changes)

Adult (associated with Bell clapper deformity)

• Urologic emergency, treat within 6hrs
  • Surgical exploration with reduction and orchidopexy 
  • orchidopexy of contralateral side also recommended

• Infarction of testes. Permanent loss of testicular function, necrosis
  • innoculation of immune system with testes antigens > future immunological infertility (sympathetic orchidopathia) - non-viable testes should be removed to prevent infertility in unaffected testes

Normal role of liver in: carbohydrate metabolism
Maintains blood glucose levels- stores glycogen to reduce blood glucose, releases it and performs gluconeogenesis to increase levels
Normal and pathological (liver failure) role of liver in: fat metabolism

Normal: 
1. Oxidises fatty acids to supply energy for other body functions
2. Synthesises cholesterol, phospholipids, lipoproteins,
3. Cholesterol converted to bile salts
4. Converting excess carbs & protein into fatty acids and triglyceride (stored in adipose tissue) 

Liver failure: dysregulated ^
Normal role of liver in: protein metabolism

1. Deamination of amino acids
2. Formation of urea for removal of ammonia from body fluids
3. Formation of plasma proteins (serum albumin, aFP, CRP)
4. Interconversions of amino acids and synthesis of compounds from them
Effect of liver failure on protein metabolism

Liver failure: 
a. Protein starvation in severe cases
b. Build-up of ammonia due to loss of urea breakdown --> hepatic encephalopathy -->  coma -->  death
c. Loss of plasma proteins -->  ascites, oedema
Effect of liver failure on carbohydrate metabolism
Increased blood glucose peaks following meals
Acute clinical features of viral hepatitis?

1. Onset of fever, headache, weakness, myalgia and anorexia
2. Onset of symptoms of jaundice, dark urine, pale faeces

1. Children often asymptomatic when infected; adults 50-75% symptomatic
2. Generally self-limiting – rare fulminant hepatitis <1%

1. Acute course, recover and immunity occurs in 90% of patients
2. 10% develop chronic hepatitis, 75% of neonates will (age strong predictor of chronicity)
3. Fulminant hepatitis occurs in 1%, with destruction of 80% of the liver

1. Initial infection: 75% asymptomatic, rest may have jaundice
2. 70% develop chronic hepatitis
3. 30-50% progress to cirrhosis after 10-30 years
